on, Oxfordshire, England","Ricote, North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1353–":"circa 1353–Overleden","1353–1379":"1353–1379","1353–Male":"1353–Overleden","1365–Female":"1365–Overleden","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1307–1379":"1307–1379","1325–Female":"1325–Overleden","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","about 1353":"circa 1353","1307":"1307","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Ricote, North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1353–":"about 1353–Deceased","1353–1379":"1353–1379","1353–Male":"1353–Deceased","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1307–1379":"1307–1379","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","about 1353":"about 1353","1307":"1307","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Ricote, North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Quartermain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Quarterman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Quarterman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Germaine, Marcel, Pascal.","English (Oxfordshire and Surrey): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>quatre mayns</i>, <i>quatre mans</i> ‘four hands’, which has been taken to imply ‘mail-fisted’ but was perhaps used of a skilled craftsman or a dextrous juggler or conjuror."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":102,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Quartermain II was born about 1353, in Oxfordshire, England, his father, Richard Quartermain, was 48 and his mother, Quartermain, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Joan Grey."},"et":{"about 1353–":"umbes 1353–Surnud","1353–1379":"1353–1379","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1307–1379":"1307–1379","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","about 1353":"umbes 1353","1307":"1307","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Ricote, North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1353–":"noin 1353–Kuollut","1353–1379":"1353–1379","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1307–1379":"1307–1379","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","about 1353":"noin 1353","1307":"1307","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England","Ricote, North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1353–":"environ 1353–Décédé","1353–1379":"1353–1379","1353–Male":"1353–Décédé","1365–Female":"1365–Décédée","1379–1421":"1379–1421","1307–1379":"1307–1379","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1421":"1421","1365":"1365","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","about 1353":"environ 1353","1307":"1307","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","Ricote, North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Quartermain II est né environ 1353, à Oxfordshire, Angleterre, son père, Richard Quartermain, avait 48 ans et sa mère, Quarterma